net.cassite.style

Class Style

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.cassite.style.Style

  • public abstract class Style
extends java.lang.Object
    All functions in Style tool box are provided here.
    Let your class extends Style to avoid retyping Style. which makes your coding prettier
    Author:
    wkgcass

      • imp

        public static <T> T imp(java.lang.Object o,
                        java.lang.Class<T> cls)
        Type Conversion.
        In order to use Style's type conversion,
        the class to be converted to may contain methods like this:
        static R from(T o)
        OR the class of the object (param 'o') to convert may contain methods like this:
        toT
        e.g.
        The following definition means you can convert String to User or convert User to String. 
         class User{
 static User from(String s)...
 String toString()...
 }
        Parameters:
        o - original object
        cls - the type to convert to
        Returns:
        object of converted type

      • readOnly

        public static <R> R readOnly(R toReadOnly)
        Make an object which has interfaces to a read-only one.
        When an invocation comes, the InvocatinHandler will check the method. 
                 if methodName.contains elements in $.readOnlyToSearch
                Check whether the method has ReadOnly annotation
                        if has
                            do invoking
                        else
                            throw an exception(ModifyReadOnlyException)
        else
                Check whether the method has Writable annotation
                        if has
                            throw an exception(ModifyReadOnlyException)
                        else
                            do invoking
        Parameters:
        toReadOnly - the object to be readonly
        Returns:
        read-only object(dynamic proxy supported)

      • join

        @SafeVarargs
public static <T> java.util.List<T> join(java.util.List<T>... toJoin)
        Join lists into one, the joined list's elements are in order of argument order and original lists' element order
        you cannot modify the returned joined list's size.
        in other words, the joined list doesn't support methods like add, remove, addAll, retainAll, removeAll...
        Parameters:
        toJoin - the lists to join
        Returns:
        a joined list
